    "summary": "The Kingdom of Pontus (281–63 BC) was a Hellenistic kingdom on the southern coast of the Black Sea (in modern northern Turkey), best known as the home of [[event:1091|Mithridatic Wars]]' protagonist Mithridates VI — Rome's most persistent adversary in the eastern Mediterranean who challenged Roman expansion for twenty-five years.\n\nPontus was founded by a Persian noble family who ruled with Greek cultural trappings, making it typical of the hybrid Hellenistic kingdoms that emerged after [[event:75|Alexander the Great's Empire]]'s dissolution. The kingdom was strategically important for its access to Black Sea trade routes, its fertile agricultural hinterland, and its timber and mineral resources. Under Mithridates VI Eupator (reigned 120–63 BC), Pontus briefly became a major power, extending its control around the Black Sea and challenging Roman dominance of Asia Minor. His ordering of the Asiatic Vespers massacre of 80,000 Romans and Italians in 88 BC triggered the [[event:1091|Mithridatic Wars]], which ended with [[event:1096|Pompey's Eastern Campaigns]] crushing Pontic power. Mithridates fled to his Crimean territories and committed suicide in 63 BC after his son betrayed him.",
